  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation. Here's a comprehensive overview:\n\n1. Early Foundations (1920s-1960s)\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) efforts emerged during Prohibition era in the United States\n- Banking secrecy laws in Switzerland and other jurisdictions initially facilitated financial concealment\n\n2. Initial Formal Legislation\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive U.S. legal framework requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Established reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Created mechanisms to track potential criminal financial activities\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing recognition of money laundering as global criminal challenge\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Significant Expansion Post-9/11\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) substantially expanded money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Increased penalties and enforcement mechanisms\n- Broadened definition of money laundering activities\n\n5. Modern Regulatory Landscape\n- Comprehensive global AML frameworks\n- Increased digital transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and emerging technology regulations\n- Continued international collaboration and standardization\n\nThis progression reflects increasingly sophisticated legal approaches to preventing financial crimes.",
